    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Samaranch Leaves to Join Wife</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Bill Brink</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Brink, Bill</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>International Olympic Committee president Juan Antonio Samaranch leaves Sydney to join his ailing wife in Spain (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Less than 24 hours after presiding over the opening ceremonies of the 2000 Sydney Games, Juan Antonio Samaranch, the president of the International Olympic Committee, left for his native Spain today to join his ailing wife.</p>
        <p>Samaranch was supposed to present the first gold medal of the Games, in the women's 10-meter air rifle, but he left Sydney late this morning to return to Barcelona. An I.O.C. spokesman said that Samarach's wife, Maria Teresa, was ill and that her condition had deteriorated. There was no indication of when Samaranch would return.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Less than 24 hours after presiding over the opening ceremonies of the 2000 Sydney Games, Juan Antonio Samaranch, the president of the International Olympic Committee, left for his native Spain today to join his ailing wife.</p>
        <p>Samaranch was supposed to present the first gold medal of the Games, in the women's 10-meter air rifle, but he left Sydney late this morning to return to Barcelona. An I.O.C. spokesman said that Samarach's wife, Maria Teresa, was ill and that her condition had deteriorated. There was no indication of when Samaranch would return.</p>
        <p>Dick Pound, an I.O.C. vice president, will act on Samaranch's behalf at official functions.</p>
        <p>Bill Brink</p>
        <p>SYDNEY 2000: NOTEBOOK</p>
      </block>
